\section*{Introduction} 

The timing of life history events---phenology---can shape both ecosystem services and community dynamics. Spring phenology, for example, defines the start and overall length of the growing season---shaping forest carbon storage and species interactions \citep{Cleland2007a,Beard2019,Gu2022}. Climate change has caused spring growth to advance in many systems \citep{Menzel2006,Vitasse2021}, leading to growing concern over the impacts these changes will have.\\

Predicting these changes requires understanding the drivers of phenology both at a proximate scale---the environmental triggers of phenology each year, such as temperature and daylength---and at an ultimate scale, where long-term environmental pressures select for the different phenologies across species \citep[e.g., certain species are early or late relative to other species each year][]{Ovaskainen2013,Wolkovich2021}. At the proximate level, environmental conditions across the winter and spring cause species to start growth at different times. This is well documented for the start of growth in woody plants each year \citep{Laube2014b,Flynn2018}. Similar trends are also observed for spring phenological events across taxa, including in the timing of egg laying in birds \citep{Crick1997,DAlba2010} and the advance of spawning in amphibians \citep{Tryjanowski2003,Kusano2008}. But current work provides limited insights into the drivers of species differences \citep{Laube2014b,Chuine2016,Flynn2018}. \\

At the ultimate level, species phenologies may vary due to changing selective pressures across the growing season. Species that start growth early often risk high tissue loss---due to frost damage \citep{Sakai1987,Augspurger2009} or high herbivore apparency \citep{Wainwright2012}---but benefit from higher resource availability \citep{Rathcke1985a,Hufkens2012}. In contrast, later species face greater biotic pressures, especially from high competition for resources  \citep{Lopez2008,Wolkovich2014}. For plants, this variation in early to late season growth, may mirror the stressors from early to late successional communities, and may similarly shape phenology \citep{Laube2014b}. \\  

Different selective pressures could shape a number of species attributes related to their growth strategies, including phenology. Species with earlier phenology may produce cheaper tissues that are easily replaced if damaged \citep{Reich1999}. But later species would benefit from investing in tissues that infer greater resource retention \citep{Gorne2020}. These differences in traits, and trade-offs in allocation of resources to growth and tissue quality, can be related to a broader framework of species growth strategies and functional traits \citep[Fig. \ref{fig:concept},][]{Wolkovich2014}, where species range from acquisitive (fast) to more conservative (slow) growth strategies  \citep{Wright2004,Chave2009}. 

Globally, gradients from acquisitive to conservative strategies appear common, and form the foundation of the leaf economic and the wood economic spectra \citep{Westoby1998,Westoby2006,Wright2004,Chave2009,Diaz2016}, but they are limited in predicting trait variability \citep{Violle2012}. As a result, highly variable traits like phenology are often excluded from trait studies, leaving the relationships between broader trait syndromes and phenology largely unknown. But understanding these relationships is critical to forecasting community dynamics and responses to climate change. To date, studies have generally only examined the relationship between traits and phenology within a single site \citep[reviewed in][]{Wolkovich2014c,Wolkovich2021}% DLJune9: (reviewed in MeMegan, WolkovichClelandAoB)
, where the problem of proximate drivers causing phenological variation can be more easily ignored. But adding phenology to broader trait frameworks requires finding a way to deal with the high levels of variation in the calendar dates of phenology when measured across sites and years.  \\ % with many studies simply assuming this variability to be negligible \citep{Grime2006,Pau2011}\\

Consistently defining early to late phenology is possible using the underlying cues that predict gradients in phenology, which do not vary strongly across space and time \citep{Chuine1999,Harrington2015,Flynn2018}. For many plants, early species generally have weak (small in magnitude) responses to all three major cues of spring leafout: warm spring temperatures (forcing), cool winter temperatures (chilling) and daylength (photoperiod). In contrast, later species have stronger (larger) responses to chilling and/or photoperiod \citep{Laube2014b,Flynn2018}, and we predict to have higher forcing as well.  \\

Research exploring the relationships between phenology and plant traits has demonstrated how traits vary within a growing season relative to phenological stages \citep{McKown2013, Fajardo2016} and across species \citep{konig2018, Sporbert2022}. At the community scale, this work has shown plant phenologies to relate to traits such as height and leaf area, with taller plants exhibiting delays in phenology relative to short species. But how other trait values relate to the underlying cues of phenology remains unclear.\\

%emwMay30 -- avoid () inside () usually
Studies of spring phenology in temperate forests may provide the best opportunity to integrate phenology into functional trait research, given their cues are well understood and the strong gradients in selective environments that occur over the spring season. As in other systems, early season species trade-off high access to resources (greater soil resources and light availability) with risks of tissue loss and damage, while late season species experience a highly competitive but less risky environment. Based on these trade-offs, we predict acquisitive species to be shorter, with leaf traits favourable to higher light availability and tolerance of late spring frost (high specific leaf area, SLA, and leaf nitrogen content, LNC; Fig \ref{fig:concept}). Such species should exhibit early phenology, with weak cue responses, especially to chilling and photoperiod. Canopy species that budburst later, when competition for soil resources is greater, would then have traits associated with conservative growth--taller with denser wood \citep{Laughlin2010}---with leaf traits suited for more variable light (low SLA and LNC, Fig \ref{fig:concept}). This delayed phenology should be reflected in their higher cue responses. % high forcing, chilling, and photoperiod requirements % early-late
Seed size may similarly be predicted from this acquisitive to conservative continuum, as acquisitive species produce smaller seeds and conservative species produce larger---better provisioned---seeds (Fig \ref{fig:concept}). \\

To test these predictions of associations between budburst responses to environmental cues and common functional traits, we merged available data from trait databases (BIEN, \cite{Maitner2018} and TRY, \citet{tryDB}) with budburst data from the OSPREE database of controlled environment studies  \citep{Ettinger2020}. We developed a hierarchical Bayesian joint model that predicts phenological responses to cues based on species-level trait values, while allowing additional variation due to species. This approach takes a step towards predicting variation via species traits instead of species identity---when traits explain a significant portion of the variation, species will explain only a small amount---and forecast species phenological responses to cues based on trait values alone. % while providing new insights into the effects of traits on phenological cues. \\

