\section*{Discussion} 

% emwMay30 -- add cites below
We found species traits influenced the timing of budburst in response to the three primary cues of spring phenology: chilling, forcing and photoperiod. These trait effects were associated with earlier or later phenology following well-established gradients in growth strategies predicted by functional traits (CITES): early species tended to have traits associated with fast and acquisitive strategies while later species had traits associated with to conservative, slower strategies. We found the largest budburst responses occurred for traits related to resource acquisition and structure, with SLA, LNC, and height all showing strong responses across our three cues. In contrast, our one reproductive trait---seed mass---showed a weak response. Despite finding these general trends in trait relationships to phenology, we also found considerable variation across studies, often at a magnitude comparable to the differences observed across species.\\ % emwMay30 -- you may want to (1) cut this last sentence (since you never discuss it again -- or you could add it to the forecasting section in a new short paragraph right before the conclusions that breaks down the need for ways to reduce this noise if we want to forecast from traits to forests more, and then (2) add 1-2 sentence at the end of this paragraph that put your findings in light of other studies on trait x phenology. Something like: Our results support several single site studies of diverse plant communities (if true) where early-late active species also followed similar acquisitive to conservative growth strategies (CITES). (This would connect back to the updated-after-co-author-feedback intro better.)

\subsection*{Effects of phenology-trait relationships on community assembly} 

Our findings suggest the changing selective pressures across the early growing season may effect the temporal assembly of communities, with strong abiotic filters early in the season associated with early and acquisitive species while greater biotic pressures later were associated with later conservative species. Additionally, these traits of early budbursting species, such as shorter heights and low LNC, would allow them to grow quickly and benefit from greater light availability in the open canopy of many early-spring temperate forests. We found phenologically earlier species had traits that inferred faster return on resource investments \citep{Grime1977,Westoby1998,Chave2009} and thus may be easier to replace if lost to frost or other abiotic disturbances. In contrast, phenologically later species filled different trait space (Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits}), exhibiting a phenotype that infers greater competitive abilities and slower growth \citep{Grime1977,Westoby1998,Chave2009}, which may be necessary to compete for soil and light resources when most other species are already growing. These phenotypes can be linked to other ecological processes and species characteristics, such as species successional position, as illustrated by the differences between early and late successional species, like \emph{Alnus incana} and \emph{Quercus robur} (Fig \ref{fig:cuetraits}).\\ %  By including phenology in the trait framework, we can identify these interactions across traits and cues and tease apart the underlying mechanisms shaping species' phenology and communities.

% In our study of temperate forest communities, the relationships between budburst phenology and other plant traits allowed us to better understand the mechanisms that shape woody species phenotypes.   \\

The traits with cue responses that deviated from our expectations also offer novel insights into the tradeoffs between traits and environmental cues. All of our traits are associated with numerous aspects of species growth, and may be adaptive for reasons other than those we predicted. Contrary to our predictions, we found strong forcing cues for short trees, which could prevent frost damage or xylem cavitation under a late spring frost \citep{Clements1972,Marquis2020} and influence annual cambial meristem growth \citep{Lenz2016}. Similarly, the lack of chilling or forcing responses by high SLA individuals' could be driven by other trait attributes and environmental cues---selecting for species relative growth rates or leaf longevity---and not photosynthetic potential \citep{Westoby1998,Reich2014}. These findings highlight the complexity of determining the drivers of species trait profiles, offering novel insights into how traits affect community dynamics under variable environments.\\

\subsection*{Phenology-trait relationships under future climates} 

% emwMay30 -- we need to be careful to not flip around what predicts what and try to stick to how we modeled it (even if, of course, we don't know causation) ... ' Our findings demonstrate that the same environmental cues driving phenological traits also relate to leaf and structural traits ' I think will confuse readers. Also be really careful when you say something can 'select' for something so:  warming that favors species with certain phenological cues, and can select for specific trait syndromes -->  warming that favors species with certain phenological cues may also favor specific trait syndromes
Incorporating phenology within broader trait syndromes could aid forecasting species and community responses to climate change. While decades of research have documented phenological shifts with anthropogenic climate change, increasing research suggests a potential connection between phenological responses to warming and performance with warming, where species that shift more with phenology appear to perform better (citeCLELAND 2012 and many I think; check citations of this paper and find some new ones to cite also). Our results suggest this phenology-performance relationship could be driven in part by a suite of traits that covary with phenological cues to determine how responsive species are to warming. As species with smaller responses to all cues, especially chilling and photoperiod, would tend to advance more with warming, our results suggest these species may also grow more quickly. These results could further aid predicting the potential for invasion, as communities with similar phenologies and suites of traits, appear more susceptible to fast growing, phenological more responsive non-native species \citep{Wolkovich2011,Alexander2019,Schuster2021}.\\
% While recent phenological shifts are well documented, but there remains a high degree of unexplained variation across species and populations \citep{Vitasse2009,Wolkovich2014,Zohner2014,Vitasse2018}.
 % Our findings demonstrate that the same environmental cues driving phenological traits also relate to leaf and structural traits and thus suggest that warming that favors species with certain phenological cues, and can select for specific trait syndromes. \\
 
% emwMay30 -- lots of edits here to avoid repetition and anthropomorphic species ('able to') 
Our analytical approach and results may be especially useful to help forecast changes in forest dynamics.  By identifying the trait syndromes of forest communities and the interactions between traits and environmental cues, we can better predict how climate change will alter species growth and productivity, identify which species are most likely to be negatively impacted under future climates, and develop better strategies for climate change mitigation and conservation. For example, our results suggest warming may favor species with weak chilling and photoperiod requirements, which also are often species with acquisitive growth strategies. In contrast, conservative species with high chilling and photoperiod requirements, could face greater abiotic and biotic stress \citep{Guy2014}. Species that fail to advance phenologically with warming might experience more competition \citep{Carter2018,Alexander2019}, as early species begin growth earlier and earlier in the season have more time to deplete resources. Growing under warmer summer conditions could also expose species to greater drought stress \citep{Frelich2010}. In addition to altering the timing and interactions between species within a season, species trait syndromes have the potential to redefine the environmental conditions under which growth occurs.\\

\emph{Conclusions}: Our study is one of the first to jointly model budburst cues and timing with other trait relationships. Using this approach we identified trends in phenological cues based on species-level trait variation, while accounting for the high degree of uncertainty that arises when combining datasets of diverse communities. Despite the diversity within our dataset being limited by the availability of data, our dataset represents the most comprehensive trait syndrome available, making it an important first step to identify general trends that scale across populations and species. Further, our findings demonstrate how traits and phenologies are inextricably linked to varying strategies for growth, with gradients from strong abiotic filters early in the growing season to greater biotic pressures later in the season, producing varying selective pressures that may shape the assembly of communities. By including phenology in the existing trait framework, we identified the key interactions across traits and cues and can tease apart the underlying mechanisms shaping species phenology across communities. Our work highlights the complexity of interactions shaping communities, and represents holistic approach to better forecast future changes in phenologies, community assembly, and productivity of diverse ecological communities.\\ 

